    <a name="fda_labeling_medical_devices" class="bookmark"></a>
    <strong>US FDA Publishes Direct Final Rule to Amend Labeling Requirements for Medical Devices</strong>
    <p>On June 15, 2016, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) published <a href="https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2016/06/15/2016-13989/use-of-symbols-in-labeling?utm_content=previous&utm_medium=PrevNext&utm_source=Article" target="_blank">a final rule, 81 FR 38911, Use of Symbols in Labeling</a>. The final rule revises FDA labeling requirements of medical devices and certain biological products concerning the inclusion of symbols or graphical representations of information. The new requirement will be effective on September 13, 2016.</p>
    <a href="javascript://" class="learnmore">Read More</a><br />
    <div class="moretext">
        <p>In the final rule, the key amendments to the labeling regulations related to medical devices are summarized below:</p>
        <ol>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">In 21 CFR 801.15, a new section c(I) is added to address the possible labeling formats:<br />
                <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
                    <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Labeling information in English language</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">In case of distributing solely in Puerto Rico or in a Territory where the predominant language is the one other than English, the predominant language may be used instead of English in labeling information.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">A symbol accompanied by explanatory English text or predominant language text</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">A symbol not accompanied by explanatory text only when the symbol is:<br />
                        <ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
                            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Contained in FDA recognized standard in section 514 (c) of the Food, Drug and Cosmetic (FD&C) Act;</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Used according to the specifications for use of the symbol set forth in FD&C Act section 514 (c) recognition; and</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Explained in paper or electronic symbols glossary that is included in the labeling for the device and the labeling within the packaging</li>
                        </ol>
                    </li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">A symbol not accompanied by explanatory text only when the symbol is:<br />
                        <ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
                            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Established in a standard developed by Standards Development Organization (SDO);</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Not contained in FDA recognized standard in section 514 (c) of the FD&C Act;</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Determined by the manufacturer to be likely to be read and understood by the ordinary individual under customary conditions of purchase and use in compliance with section 5802 (c) of the FD&C Act;</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Used according to specifications for use of the symbol set forth in the SDO developed standard; and</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Explained in paper or electronic symbols glossary that is included in the labeling for the device and the labeling within the packaging</li>
                        </ol>
                    </li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Symbol “Rx only” or “℞ only”</li>
                </ol>
            </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">In 21 CFR 801.109 Prescription devices, section (b) is revised to add symbol “Rx only” or “℞ only” as one of the exemption criterion for “adequate directions for use” requirement</li>
        </ol>
    </div><br />
</div>

