    <strong>Thailand Issues New Requirements for Food Nutrition Labelling</strong>
    <p>In June 2016, the Thailand Ministry of Public Health issued <a href="http://iodinethailand.fda.moph.go.th/food_54/law/data/announ_moph/V.English/No.374_Food_products.pdf" target="_blank">Notification, No. 374</a>, Guideline Daily Amounts (GDA), a new food nutrition labeling requirement for certain types of food. The new GDA requirement aims to support the consumer by providing preventive measures for nutritional problems through detailed nutrients information.</p>
    <a href="javascript://" class="learnmore">Read More</a><br />
    <div class="moretext">
        <p>The following foods are required to include GDA information on the nutrition label:</p>
        <ol>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Snack foods</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Chocolate and same kind products</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Bakery products</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Semi processed foods such as noodles</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Chilled and frozen ready-to-eat meals</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The GDA shall be provided with energy value, sugar, fat and sodium content according to the following format:</p>
        <ol>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">The information of energy value, sugar, fat and sodium are separated into four vertical cylinders (See following example GDA label)</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">The color of the frames shall be in contrasting colors with the background (black, dark blue or white) </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">The background color of cylinders shall be in white</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom:5px;">Each line inside the cylinders shall be in black or dark blue and they shall be in the same color of the letters inside</li>
        </ol>
